    en: "The State of New York generally cannot be sued without its consent. The Court of Claims Act (CCT) provides that consent — waiving sovereign immunity for specified claims. Section 10 sets strict deadlines: personal injury claims must be filed within 90 days of accrual; wrongful death within 90 days of appointment of a personal representative; contract claims within 6 months; and property damage within 90 days. Failure to meet the deadline is typically fatal absent specific late-filing relief under CCT 10(6). Claims are heard by a Judge of the Court of Claims without a jury. Separately, wrongful-conviction claims under CCT 8-b and specific damage caps apply to certain categories. Claims against counties, cities, and other municipalities are governed by General Municipal Law 50-e, not the Court of Claims Act — see notice-of-claim-municipal-ny."
